#This subroutine shuffles an array
sub shuffle
{
    my $array = shift;
    my $i = @$array;
    while ( --$i )
    {
        my $j = random(0,$i,1);
        @$array[$i,$j] = @$array[$j,$i];
    }
}

############################################

Context("LimitedNumeric");

$int = random(0,9,1);
$dec = random(2,9,1);

@nums = ();
$nums[0] = -($int+$dec/10);
$ans0 = $nums[0];
$nums[1] = -($int+$dec/100);
$ans1 = $nums[1];
$nums[2] = -($int+$dec/1000);
$ans2 = $nums[2];

shuffle( ~~@nums);

##############################################

TEXT(beginproblem());

BEGIN_PGML

Order these decimals from biggest to smallest: 

    [`` [@$nums[0]@], [@$nums[1]@], [@$nums[2]@] ``]

    [___________]{$ans2} > [___________]{$ans1} > [___________]{$ans0}

END_PGML

##############################################

BEGIN_PGML_SOLUTION

The number [`[$ans0]`] is like [`[$int]`] dollars and [`[$dec]`] dimes, because the digit [`[$dec]`] is in the tenth place.

The number [`[$ans1]`] is like [`[$int]`] dollars and [`[$dec]`] cents, because the digit [`[$dec]`] is in the hundredth place.

The number [`[$ans2]`] is like [`[$int]`] dollars and [@numberWord($dec)@] tenths of a cent, because the digit [`[$dec]`] is in the thousandth place.

However, all these number are negative. For negative numbers, the smaller its absolute value, the bigger the number. For example, [`-1>-2`].

This is why the solution is:

    [`` [$ans2] > [$ans1] > [$ans0] ``]

END_PGML_SOLUTION

